-{"id":"rust_proxy-xw7","title":"Load balancing across healthy proxies","description":"## Overview

Instead of using a single "active" proxy with failover only on health failure, actively distribute traffic across multiple healthy proxies using configurable strategies.

## Why This Matters

Currently, rust_proxy uses a single active proxy and only switches on failure. With multiple healthy proxies, users want to:
- **Improve performance**: Use parallel capacity of multiple proxies
- **Improve reliability**: No single point of failure
- **Better resource utilization**: Spread load across available proxies
- **Automatic optimization**: Use the fastest proxy without manual selection

## Load Balancing Strategies

### 1. Single (Current Behavior)
Use one active proxy, failover only on health failure. This remains the default for backward compatibility.

### 2. Round-Robin
Cycle through healthy proxies sequentially. Simple, fair distribution.

### 3. Least-Latency
Prefer the proxy with lowest recent latency (uses health check latency data). Automatically optimizes for performance.

### 4. Weighted
Distribute by configured weights. Useful when proxies have different capacities or costs.

## Configuration

```toml
[settings]
# Load balancing strategy: "single" (default), "round_robin", "least_latency", "weighted"
load_balance_strategy = "least_latency"

[[proxies]]
id = "mesh-us"
url = "http://us-wa.proxymesh.com:31280"
priority = 1
weight = 60    # For weighted strategy: 60% of traffic

[[proxies]]
id = "mesh-eu"
url = "http://eu.proxymesh.com:31280"
priority = 2
weight = 40    # For weighted strategy: 40% of traffic
```

## Implementation Approach

The RuntimeState already tracks health per proxy. We extend it with:
1. Proxy selection method that considers strategy
2. Round-robin counter (atomic)
3. Latency tracking integration (already have this from health checks)
4. Weight-based random selection

## Example Behavior

With `least_latency` strategy and three healthy proxies:
- mesh-us: 45ms average latency
- mesh-eu: 120ms average latency
- mesh-jp: 200ms average latency

Traffic is routed to mesh-us (fastest) until it becomes unhealthy or its latency increases.

With `round_robin`, requests cycle: mesh-us -> mesh-eu -> mesh-jp -> mesh-us -> ...

## Status Command Output

```
Load Balancing: least_latency
  mesh-us: ✓ healthy (45ms) - ACTIVE
  mesh-eu: ✓ healthy (120ms)
  mesh-jp: ✓ healthy (200ms)
```

## Success Criteria

- All strategies implemented and working
- Strategy configurable via config file
- Status command shows load balancing info
- Backward compatible (single strategy = current behavior)
- Performance impact minimal

